			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				I'm running mysql with the --skip-grant-tables option right now because I can't seem to get the root login fixed.  This is very insecure and I'm a little worried about leaving it this way, though my user base is only about 32 people, theoretically any of 50,000 people could connect to the server and do whatever they wanted to.  This is on RH9 (not fedora), I figure up2date must have screwed something up along the way (it's screwed up more than a few packages beyond belief, still digging through the rubble, it's definitely not the RH version of Windows Update).
<br />

<br />
Anyway, I have tried the following:
<br />

<br />
1) starting the daemon with --skip-grant-tables and manually editing the privilege table to reflect new root account information, killing the process, and starting regular daemon (can't log in as root user)
<br />

<br />
2) starting the daemon with --skip-grant-tables, using mysqladmin to reset password, kill process, start daemon regularly (can't log in as root user)
<br />

<br />
I don't really know what else to try, those two attempts were procedures straight out of the mysql documentation for lost passwords.  Also, no other database privileges are corrupt, my php activity logger can log into its database fine, etc.
<br />

<br />
I'm kind of a noob to this anyway, so any ideas are appreciated.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
